│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp"], [11290, 11341,            │
│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1.          │
│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe Alive2 report shows that SLP's first            │
│ transformation produces a target that is more poisonous than the source.      │
│ Concretely, SLP replaces a pair of scalar extensions (zext from %1[0] and     │
│ sext from %0[0]) feeding an add with a shufflevector of the two inputs,       │
│ followed by extracting both elements and sign-extending both of them. This    │
│ silently changes the zero-extend of %1[0] to a sign-extend. In the provided   │
│ counterexample, %1[0] = 0xfffffff8, and sign-extending that to i64 yields -8, │
│ which feeds an \"add nuw nsw i64\"; this path becomes poison under Alive2     │
│ semantics, whereas the source (zext + sext) is non-poison.\n\nThus, the IR    │
│ modification at the first transformation point causes a change in the         │
│ signedness of one extension (zext -> sext), violating semantics in the        │
│ presence of poison and nowrap flags.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\n- SLP        │
│ decides to vectorize a list of length 2 consisting of %6 = zext i32 %5 to i64 │
│ and %4 = sext i32 %3 to i64.\n- It emits a shufflevector combining %1 and %0  │
│ with mask <0,3> to build a 2-lane vector and then extracts both lanes and     │
│ sign-extends each.\n- The debug log shows the cost model recognizing          │
│ \"alternate extension, which should be truncated.\", indicating that the      │
│ vectorizer is aware of alternating extension kinds.\n- Yet the final IR shows │
│ both extensions being sext, i.e., the alternation of sext/zext is lost. This  │
│ loss happens during the first transformation, before any later combination or │
│ CSE.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe vectorizer is treating alternating cast  │
│ operations (sext and zext) as an \"alternate\" pair that can be bundled and   │
│ then reconstituted via a shuffle. However, the emission path for tiny trees   │
│ does not preserve per-lane cast opcodes when it performs the shufflevector    │
│ and extracts back to scalars. Instead, it applies a uniform sign-extension to │
│ both extracted scalars (sext), which is incorrect if one lane was originally  │
